channel.title: Interleaved RSS Feed
channel.description: This is an interleaved feed of the most recent entries from each RSS source, skipping any feeds with errors.

item.title: Liverpool Sends a Message to Far-Right Rioters: Not Here
item.description: Liverpool, in northern England, has a long history of organized action. That tradition continued this week, with counterprotesters delivering a firm rejection of anti-immigrant violence.

item.title: Israel Launches Another Offensive in Gaza’s South Amid Push for Cease-Fire
item.description: The country’s prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, said he would send negotiators what leaders including President Biden called the presentation of a “final” cease-fire proposal.

item.title: Coca-Cola is going reverse Yankee by selling €1 billion of Euro debt to cover a potential tax charge
item.description: The beverage company has been in a long-drawn dispute with tax authorities in the U.S. over a $16 billion charge that it could possibly owe.

item.title: The Reason Trump and Vance Really Hate Being Called ‘Weird’
item.description: It reminds voters how far out of the mainstream Republicans have gotten.

item.title: Carles Puigdemont Flees Spain Again After Rally, His Lawyer Says
item.description: The Catalan separatist leader, who has been living in self-imposed exile since spearheading an illegal referendum on independence in 2017, vanished almost as quickly as he had surfaced this week.

item.title: Fed president throws doubt onto September rate cut Wall Street is desperate for
item.description: "We should be looking for the worst in the data rather than the best."

item.title: As Ukraine Presses an Advance Into Russia, Its Goals Remain Unclear
item.description: Despite quick gains in the western Russian region of Kursk, analysts question whether Ukraine can maintain the momentum.

item.title: Liverpool Sends a Message to Far-Right Rioters: Not Here
item.description: Liverpool, in northern England, has a long history of organized action. That tradition continued this week, with counterprotesters delivering a firm rejection of anti-immigrant violence.

item.title: Apple changes up App Store rules in Europe once again as EU threat of non-compliance grows
item.description: The commission said it "will assess Apple's eventual changes to the compliance measures, also taking into account any feedback from the market, notably developers".

item.title: Trump Tries to Retake the Spotlight, and Ukraine Pushes Into Russia
item.description: Plus, Noah Lyles’s Olympic run with Covid.

item.title: Belarus Shuns Athletes Who Protested Lukashenko
item.description: Many elite athletes who spoke against their autocratic leader must watch on the sidelines while those who stayed quiet or showed loyalty compete in Paris.

item.title: Delta expects $380 million in lost sales from the CrowdStrike outage that forced it to cancel thousands of flights
item.description: The airline on Thursday confirmed that it was pursuing legal claims against CrowdStrike and Microsoft Corp. to recover damages.

item.title: A Swing in Momentum
item.description: We explain the state of the 2024 race.

item.title: Olympic Breaking’s Key Player Is a D.J. From Brooklyn
item.description: Stephen Fleg will help provide the soundtrack for a new sport’s Olympic debut. He gets to pick the songs, and the competitors have no idea what he’ll play.

item.title: German giant Siemens beat profit estimates on the back of AI boom and demand for electrification
item.description: Siemens had long been a producer of heavy industrial equipment but has in recent years sought to shift its focus towards digital technology and factory automation.
